    ns1:numberOfCredits 4.0 ;
    ns1:otherInformation """Supplementary reference material:
CONNELL, D.W. (1997): Basic Concepts of Environmental Chemistry. Lewis Publishers, Boca Raton, Fl. (U.S.A.)
CROSBY, D.G. (1998): Environmental Toxicology and Chemistry. Oxford University Press, Nueva York.
KLAASSEN, C.D. y WATKINS III, J.B. (eds.) (2003): Casarett & Doull?s essentials of Toxicology. McGraw-Hill, Nueva York.
MANAHAN, S.E. (1994): Environmental Chemistry, 6th Edition. CRC Press. Boca Raton, Fl. (U.S.A.)
U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (1989): Risk Assessment Guidance for Superfund (RAGS) Part A. Chapter 6: Exposure Assessment. http://www.epa.gov/oswer/riskassessment/ragsa/pdf/ch6.pdf
U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (1989): Risk Assessment Guidance for Superfund (RAGS) Part A. Chapter 7: Toxicity Assessment. http://www.epa.gov/oswer/riskassessment/ragsa/pdf/ch7.pdf
U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (1989): Risk Assessment Guidance for Superfund (RAGS) Part A. Chapter 8: Risk Characterization. http://www.epa.gov/oswer/riskassessment/ragsa/pdf/ch8.pdf
U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (1986a): Carcinogen Risk Assessment. 51 Federal Register 33992.
U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (1992): Guidelines for Exposure Assessment. EPA/600/Z-92/001

The subject is related with the following Sustainable Development Objectives:
SDG 3 Good Health and Well-being
Ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all at all ages.
This course directly supports SDG 3 by equipping students with tools to assess and manage health risks from contaminated sites, helping to prevent disease and protect vulnerable populations from environmental hazards.
SDG 6 Clean Water and Sanitation
Ensure availability and sustainable management of water and sanitation for all.
Contaminated sites often affect groundwater and surface water quality. By analyzing exposure pathways and risk scenarios, students learn to identify threats to water safety and propose mitigation strategies aligned with this goal.
SDG 12 Responsible Consumption and Production
Ensure sustainable consumption and production patterns.
Understanding the legacy of industrial pollution and its health impacts encourages future professionals to advocate for cleaner production practices and responsible waste management, contributing to more sustainable development.
SDG 15 Life on Land
Protect, restore and promote sustainable use of terrestrial ecosystems, sustainably manage forests, combat desertification, and halt and reverse land degradation and halt biodiversity loss.
This course contributes to SDG 15 by addressing how contaminated sites degrade land quality and threaten terrestrial ecosystems. Understanding these risks supports efforts to remediate polluted environments and protect biodiversity, while also reducing indirect health risks to human populations."""@es ;
